</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>An arrow <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  x \to  y]]></fr:tex> in a <fr:link
type="local"
href="erct-000B.xml"
addr="erct-000B"
title="Precategory">precategory</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[C]]></fr:tex> is called an <fr:em><fr:strong>isomorphism</fr:strong></fr:em> when either of there exists an inverse to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>, i.e. an arrow <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g\colon  y \to  x]]></fr:tex> that is simultaneously a <fr:link
type="local"
href="erct-000F.xml"
addr="erct-000F"
title="Section-retraction pair in a precategory">section and a retraction</fr:link> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>We shall write <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  x \cong  y]]></fr:tex> to denote an isomorphism from <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter><fr:tree
